                </a></li></ul></div><p><strong>Figure 7.  <span>Schematic model of Aur-A overexpression in cancer.</span></strong></p><a id="article1.body1.sec3.fig1.caption1.p1" name="article1.body1.sec3.fig1.caption1.p1"></a><p>During mitosis, Aur-A is phosphorylated on Ser51 in normal cells. At mitotic exit, Aur-A is de-phosphorylated by PP2A and ubiquitylated by APC<sup>Cdh1</sup>. On the other hand, Aur-A is constitutively phosphorylated on Ser51 in cancer cells. Therefore, Aur-A can not be ubiquitylated and consequently accumulated in cancer cells.</p>
